segments.text: In the afternoon and sitting in the nice, nice living room.
Cluttered.
No, I didn't say that.
Looking out into the backyard, talking to Mrs. Rutter about her memories of some great years here.
And now we're going to stop and see if the machine is working.
If you want to go back to Austin, if that's important, I can name a few.
All right, let's begin by, Mrs. Rutter, by you telling me and this machine and anybody that would listen to this material later about your growing up.
Where did you grow up and go to high school and so forth?
Oh, that's a long story.
I grew up on a ranch in Menard County after having come from a ranch in Sutton County.
My dad bought that ranch in Menard County from G. Raleigh White's youngest brother, Johnny.
in 1927, but I had a brother that still had a senior year in Sonora, and so we didn't move down there until the following year.
And this was, I said, I've said it's kind of in the middle of nowhere.
It's in the middle of several small towns.
It's 21 from Mason, Texas, 23 from Menard, 26 from Junction, and 36 from Brady.
So that's where I grew up.
I did all the things that kids did at that time.
At the age of 12, I rode a horse to school.
14 miles round trips, seven there and seven back, to a little school in London.
I said, sounded pretty good to say you went to school in London for two years, but when you said you rode a horse to get there, it didn't sound so good.
And then when I was 14, my mother wanted me to go to a little larger school, which wasn't very large at that, which would have been Menard, 23 miles.
So they bought me a little Ford Sport Roadster with a rumble seat, and I thought I was about the cutest thing around.
Green.
I drove to school at the age of 14.
We didn't have to have a driver's license then.
And that was in Menard?
Mm-hmm, I went to school in Menard.
You graduated from high school there?
Mm-hmm.
How many in your senior class?
36, and I was number one.
You were number one of 36?
Yeah.
And this is what year?
1932, and then you go off to college?
To University of Texas at the age of 16.
I was so young, I didn't realize how young I was.
But I got along fine.
I served two years on student government, and I was present at the dormitory I lived in, a few odds and ends.
Had, you know, a lot of nice friends, but I don't really keep up with them now.
It's not like A&M.
Did you know John and Nellie Connolly?
Yes, yes.
He was on student government, too.
Jake Pickle was my good buddy.
Describe them as college students.
Oh, John and Nellie, that was a glamour pair of the university.
He was so good-looking, and she was pretty, and...
She was the university's sweetheart.
That's what I heard.
And of course, he was.
Was he present in the student body?
He was present in the student body, but not until after I was out.
I guess he must have been in law school.
When I got there as a freshman, Alan Shearer was present in the student body.
And he was a good one.
And it's so funny that the politicians came from that group then.
Now there's more Aggies than UT.
But let's see, John Connolly was Jake Pickles, chairman of his election committee.
I don't know.
I'm not thinking straight.
When Jake ran for student body president, John was his campaign manager, is what I'm trying to say.
And then John was president of the student body the next year.
But Jake, of course, went around with little
Pickles.
No, they had real pickles at that time, real pickles.
And he still has these little plastic pickles he pins on his lapel.
And we're still good friends.
We used to pick Jake up when he was hitchhiking from Big Spring to Austin.
He was a poor boy.
Now, when you went to the university, what was your major and what did you think your career was going to be?
Let's don't talk about that.
It's funny.
I had a brother-in-law who had graduated there two years before I went, and he's the one that influenced me.
And I was a tennis player.
Can't believe that now.
But I did, and I didn't quit playing tennis

1973 suddenly I couldn't get around over the court so I majored in physical education although I had never had a lesson in it in my life but I played tennis that was it and I my brother-in-law said well and he knew that I wasn't greatly fond of math or foreign language you didn't have to have those for that major you had to have sciences but you didn't have to so anyway that's what I did and I graduated from UT
I had been 20 less than a month.
And that was too young to get it.
Well, Earl had come down when I was a senior and told me to apply.
They were putting it on in Brady where he was coaching football at the time.
And I almost didn't get the job because of my age and I hadn't had any experience because they were putting this department on.
But anyway, I taught it in Brady.
About midsummer, he had gone down to check me out down there, the superintendent had, and decided he'd hire me.
So this is 1930?
You mentioned this young man, Earl.
When did you first meet him?
Oh, gosh, I was a freshman at UT.
We started dancing together at the dances, that's all.
How did...
I knew who he was because he was in Tarleton when my older brother was.
See, Earl was six years older than I.
And...
My brother would bring his annuals home, and Earl was captain of the football team.
Good-looking Lord, I thought he was something else.
And so I didn't have to be introduced to him.
And he knew that I was my brother's little sister, you know.
But I was a freshman, and we started dancing together.
And then from that, I guess when I was a junior, he started asking me for dates in summertime and holidays, things like that.
So you, when you were back home?
Yeah, when I was back home.
All right, now he was, by that time he was...
Coaching football in Brady.
When he first got out of A&M in 1932, he couldn't find a job.
He dug ditches for the highway department.
They were building a road between Eden and Menard.

and he was digging ditches for 25 cents an hour now his major was what industrial industrial education yeah but he didn't he didn't use that either any more than i i taught one year and at that time uh they wouldn't hire a married teacher in brady and i guess you know if you your husband was employed by the school system and so i taught one year and i
I made the grand sum total of $900, just made $100 a year for nine months.
You didn't teach in the summertime, so you didn't get any money in the summertime.
And if it hadn't been that my parents paid my first month's room and board, bought my father clothes, I'd have been in the hole.
I came out with $40, which I spent before we got married the 12th of June.
And he had exactly $80.
We got married on $80 in faith.
My, my.
So you all got married at the end of your first year out of the university.
In June the 12th of 1937.
And he was the football coach.
Was he the head coach at Brady High School?
At Brady.
Or was he the only football coach?
Well, he had one substitute.
I mean, one assistant.
I don't know why I said substitute.
But now they have got the biggest coaching staff, and I bet you there's no more players.
But he made, I think, the grand total of $135 a month for nine months, just like I got paid nine months.
But, you know, and we didn't think anything about he worked long hours, I worked long hours.
They had me, I was so young and full of life at that time, hard to remember, that they made me sponsor of everything they could think of.
I had never played volleyball, but I got to sponsor the volleyball club, which met before school, had to be up there at 7.30 in the morning.
And then after school in the afternoon, I sponsored the pep squad.
I had to work out all the halftime things.
And at night, I was sponsored a senior class, so I had to direct plays and whatever else they had going.
About how many were in the senior class?
In Brady?
Right.
You know, I don't remember.
It seemed like a lot.
I not only taught in the high school, but the junior high.
And Mr. Rutter, he coached, but what else?
Football, what were his other duties?
When he first signed on there to coach, they gave him five different subjects to teach.
That was murder.
And the couple that he lived with before his mother moved over there, his father died in 1935,
And he had started coaching there in 1933, I guess.
But he had to teach all those courses, and one of them was chemistry, and he didn't even like chemistry.
Anyway, go ahead.
No, I'm just thinking about all the duties.
All right, when you all got married, what was your housing accommodation that you first lived in?
Oh, Lord.
Well, we first...
had the hot side of a duplex.
I don't really know.
I never did really know what rent he paid, but it was a little more than he thought we need to pay.
So there was a doctor who had a big old two-story frame house and built a brick, nice brick home.
And they turned that into four apartments.
So we had the upstairs apartment on the right, and it had one bedroom.
And then it had a little, I don't know what you'd call it, but it was over where you drove the car underneath the portico shade or whatever.
And it was screened.
So we rented out the one bedroom for $12 a month to the old maid librarian.
And we slept on that little screened-in porch.
Took the flu and everything else that way.
But that was how tight money was.
Sure.
And she shared the bath and the kitchen.
Because the Depression was still.
And I didn't cook.
I didn't know how to cook.
And Earl loved to eat.
He always did.
Then we were there one more year.
And he got the job as coach at Tarleton.
And that suited him just fine because he put me back in school to learn how to cook.
All right.
And so that's the fall of 39?
No, not that far along.
Eight.
Or was it?
Yeah, 38.
Yeah.
Yeah.
And since I couldn't teach, since they wouldn't let me teach regular teaching,
After that first year, they made me their chief substitute, which didn't make any sense.
And whatever school was lacking a teacher, I would go teach it.
Now, that's in Brady?
In Brady still.
So the last year in Brady, that's what I did.
Among other things, these non-paying jobs like chairman of the Red Cross Drive and stuff like that.
I don't know.
They found things for me to do, so I wouldn't be idle.
Now, I presume Brady was receptive to a new young lady, though living there.

they were oh they were brady was always a nice little friend of the town that's what i would and g raleigh white he had the most interesting family see there were four men raleigh was the oldest raleigh charlie willie and johnny johnny was the one that my dad bought the ranch from his his headquarter ranch and then they had two sisters mrs wall and mrs wolf mrs wolf
was the youngest in the family, and she was a lovely person.
And when she heard that Earl and I were gonna get married, she had me come over.

And she said, now, Margaret, I have a wedding arch, and I've forgotten the number exactly, 30-something couples have married under that arch, and I want you and Earl to get married under it, because nobody has ever parted ways that got married under my arch.
So my dad came in in the pickup and picked up the arch, and they had the florist decorate it, and we married.
at the ranch.
We had a very small, well, my mother had just been in Scott & White in Temple for a long time.
And my sister, she had a miscarriage.
She got up the day of our wedding.
And so I pretty well engineered my own wedding.
I had to.
And so I thought, I'm not gonna, in fact, my parents had built the house my senior year in college.
So it was nice and new, so I just decided I'd get married right there, under Mrs. Wolf's arch.
And then you moved to Tarleton, and y'all are in Tarleton how long?
We're there from 38 to 41, because, see, 41 is when he was called into service.
He had his commission from A&M when he graduated in 32.
Right, so in those years, in the 30s, after y'all got married, did he go to National Guard meetings or anything?
Reserve, all the time.
Is that right?
Yeah, and every summer that we were, every summer,
He had two weeks summer camp.
And where was that normally?
Well, it could be at Fort Hood.
It could be at, I can't remember the place, in Louisiana.
Camp, if you said it, I'd say that's it.
Oh, boy.
I can't think.
On this side of Louisiana in the swamp.
Yeah.
It's not a pretty place, I don't think.
So he was normally in the southwest.
Yeah.
At summer camp.
And that, did that come early in the summer usually or late?
Yeah, it came, it usually coincided with Jane's birthday and Father's Day.
Jane felt like she was, it wasn't very funny for her because her dad was never for her birthday.
And her birthday was 16th of June, so that's about the time.
At Tarleton, he coached football, and what other duties did he have?
Well, he may have taught a course or two.
I don't really remember.
I guess he did, but...
He mainly coached, and that's where we were when our first son was born.
We were there from 38 to 41, at our first home there.
And he was so ready to go into the service that he sold that home before he even got his orders, and that scared me to death.
As you look back on it now, do you think that he enjoyed coaching?
Oh, yeah.
He had a way of working with young people that was just really good.
And did you enjoy being a coach's wife?
Oh, yeah.
The only thing that confused me about Stephenville was the way they'd dress.
You'd have a bridge party at night and they'd wear a long dress, and I couldn't get used to that.
My, my.
Yeah.
Now, he had gone to Tarleton...
two years, so this in a way was going back.
Going back home.
And am I correct that people for short called it JTAC, John Tarleton Agricultural College?
That's what they called the publication, the little paper that was put out.
Was that right?
JTAC.
And they may have called the school that, I don't know.
You know, other people like Clyde Wells, he went to Tarleton.
Oh, yes.
A lot of people went to Tarleton.
He's called to active duty when?
Summer of 41.
Summer of 41.
And he went to Fort Sam, Houston.
And you're left with how many children?
Well, we just had the one then.
And then Ann was born in 42.
Okay.
Courtesy of the Army.
She was born at Fort Sam, Houston.
Right.
Did you go, where did you, when he goes to active duty, where did you live?
With him.
I followed him around as far as where he was until he went overseas.
And we lived, oh golly, we were in some pretty bad places.
We went from Fort Sam Houston by way of Fort Benning up to Camp Atterbury in Indiana, and we were up there a year.
And while we were there,
He, in November, was sent to command and general staff school.
And I thought the weather was too bad to try to take the kids and come back to Texas.

And they made it very plain, they didn't want any spouses or family to come with them because they had had to condense that course down to just a little, like two months or so from a much longer course.
So I stayed there, but it was kind of a bad winter.
My two little ones, see, Ann was only six weeks old when we got there.
Ann Budd was just two years older than that, and they both got bronchopneumonia.
with him gone, so it was kind of bad.

I've learned in talking to youngsters today about the World War II era that they are astonished that there were no pickets against the war, there were no demonstrators, and that no one doubted who was going to win the war.
And I do you agree with that with that?

Yeah, and like I say Earl was so Ready to go in and he knew what he's getting into That he sold our home before he ever got his orders Right then when he went overseas you went back where I went back to Brady and
And lived.
In a little house next to a neighborhood grocery store.
It was a house that had been bought.
See, Earl in 1935 had bought a drugstore.
Everybody thought that it was his brother's because Earl bought it so his brother would have a job.
He'd gotten one of those little quickie pharmacy, whatever you get.
Didn't have to go and get a degree in it at that time.
And he didn't have a job.
He had a wife and a little boy.
So Earl saw that this came up for sale.
So he did all the arranging and getting the finance.
And what was so funny about that, and I'm getting off the subject, is C.G.
Raleigh White, who'd always been most kind to Earl, he had the commercial bank in Brady.
He was the bank.
And so Earl went there first to get the loan to put this drugstore in.
But Mr. White wasn't there, and his loan officer turned Earl down.
So he just walked around the square to the other bank, Brady National, and they loaned him the money.
And do you know, until he died, he sent every check back to the Brady National Bank because they had loaned him money.
And anyway, John was to run it.
because he had his little pharmacy thing, and it didn't work out.
We learned a lot from that.
All right.
When does he go overseas?
He went overseas in 1940.
I could follow 42 or 43 now.
Haskell, I'm not positive on that.
It's one or the other, 42 or 43.
Let's see.
Where had we been?
Hmm.
You know, I should have written all that down, but I didn't.
All right, now, is his first combat experience D-Day?
Yeah.
Okay, that's 1944.
But they went, they trained, yeah, sure, but they trained in England.
In England.
So it must have been fall of 1943 that he went over.
All right, between the time he first went overseas and...
Well, did you get to see him at all after that first trip he first went to Europe until the war was over?
No.
I went up.
He was at Fort Dix is where they were before they were sent overseas in New Jersey.
And he called me to come up there.
Earl was really good at giving orders, and he gave them to me, too.
And he called...
late Wednesday night, and I didn't even have a telephone yet.
I had just moved into this little house.
And my neighbor came over and got me.
And he called me at her house.
And Wednesday night, he wanted me at Fort Dix by Saturday noon.
And I had to figure out how to get there.
I took my first plane ride, but I got bounced off.
You know, you had to have a priority.
to be able to fly and of course I didn't have one and so anyway I finally got there but by train instead of plane and I stayed up there ten days seeing him before he went overseas.
Now while he's in Europe about how often did you write him and he write you?
Oh we wrote a lot and I have all those letters
There's a book over there on the organ bench now that has two of his letters printed in it.
When they had this exhibit, I guess it started out in 1990.
Ann and I went down to the luncheon in the LBJ Library.
And it was there for about three or four months.
Then they made the rounds.
And see, people from all over the United States had something in that exhibit.
And then they made the rounds of all the presidential libraries in the country.
Ended up in the National Archives in 1995, maybe.
And then I got them back.
But they asked me what value I'd put on those for insurance.
I said I wouldn't have any idea.
So they put $1,000 each.
And I've forgotten what value they put on the picture of Earl they used.
I want to chat with you about those later, but let's proceed.
So did you write him once a week?
Oh, more.
More than that?
More than that, yeah.
And about how often did he write?
He was good at writing, except when he was in the middle of the Battle of the Bulge.
See, Earl was in the, of course D-Day was scary enough.
He went in with 225 men, and you know that story, I'm sure.
And end of the first day, this 90 could bear arms.
I mean, it was murder, because the British guide boat had started out taking them to the wrong point and made them late.
Anyway, after that, it was so spectacular.
And it was published by the War Department in a little book called Small Unit Actions, where they figured, picked four out of the war.
And that was number one in the book.

anyway then he was also in the Battle of the Bulge oh yeah see that that was so spectacular what had happened on D-Day that they gave him a much larger command regiment in the 28th division infantry division and they had just come out of the Battle of the Hurtgen Forest see he was given command of this regiment on the 8th of December and on the 16th of December this was 1944 the Germans
started their last counteroffensive, which was the Battle of the Bulge.
And they were right in the thick of that because they were thinly spread, and I'm sure the Germans were able to determine that.
And so they came marching through, and Earl's regiment was on the southern part of this arc.
It was the 109th Regiment.
It was on the southern part.
Then the 110th was in the center, and it was practically annihilated.
And the 112th was on the top part of the arc.
And so they came marching through.
And Earl's regiment was given credit for blunting the German attack, because they just pivoted and dug in and camouflaged.
It was snow.
And the Germans came marching up.
It said it was kind of similar to don't fire till you see the whites of their eyes.
And when they got up close, then they fired on him.
He gave the command.
And I did have all kinds of articles about that from the Philadelphia Inquirer because it was a Pennsylvania outfit.
And they said something about 2,500 Germans lay bleeding in the snow.
Anyways, pretty much of a battle.
All right.
With you back in Brady,
When did you first learn that he had been involved in the invasion?
Yes, ma'am.
Okay, I can tell you exactly.
When I was up in New Jersey for that 10 days before he left to go overseas, we were with this cute couple from, both were native New Yorkers, Alice and Jerry Wilkin.
Jerry was one of Earl's officers in the Ranger Battalion.
And Alice and I got to be fast friends in that 10 days, because we'd go into Philadelphia one night, the four of us, and then New York another night.
We just had a real good time.
And she and I just hit it off.
She was younger than I.
But she worked in New York, and she talked about her.
In the summertime, she got a two-week vacation.
So I asked her, why didn't she come to Texas and spend it with me?
So she decided she would.
So I had just picked her up in San Antonio.
She flew in down there.
And we'd spent the night at Randolph, because my college roommate and her husband were out there.
And then we went on over to Austin, and we were in the Stephen F. Austin Hotel right there on Congress Avenue.
And about 3 in the morning, the newsboys down below were yelling, extra, extra, read all about it.
I don't know that they even do that anymore.
I don't think so.
And so I got up, threw something on, went down, got a paper.
And I said the thing that was so different from now, we couldn't find a place to find a radio that wasn't in TV.
And we went up and down Congress Avenue trying to find a place that we could listen to the radio to see what was going on.
We finally ended up in the back of Leon's shoe store.
And we listened to it for quite a while.
And then we got in the car and drove on to Brady.
That's where I was living at the time.
Now, did you know that his unit was in it?
Oh, without a doubt.
We knew that they were in it.
And we did not know that her husband was almost killed that first day.
Earl was wounded twice.
He got shot through the leg.
I've got pictures that he sent me a little snapshot where he's got on shorts.
And he said, if you'll notice, just about six inches above the left knee, you can still see the scar where the bullet came out.
Well, you can.
But then I had this other picture where he's standing in his uniform up on top of the cliff.
And on that same leg, same place, there's that blood.
So I put the two together.
But anyway, Jerry was almost killed, her husband.
And she didn't find it out until she got home, got back to New York.
Now, when did you, do you remember how long it was before you got a letter from him after D-Day?
Was it a week or a month or?
It was probably about the time, the first ones in that book, it just said somewhere in France.
It didn't say where.
And actually, the San Angelo paper was the paper out in that area.
And so Alice and my two little ones and I had gone out to my sister-in-law because my brother was on Saipan.
And she was there with her two little ones.
And we were
Always good friends.
Pat died last year.
But anyway, she was a grade ahead of me in high school.
And we liked to go out there.
She was a lot of fun.
And so a fella in Menard called me, real nice fella, had a grocery store there, asked me if I'd seen the paper.
And I said, no.
He said, well, your husband's picture's on the front page that he's been wounded.
I said, oh, golly.
So went in, got the paper.
She lived 18 miles out.
And it didn't say how badly or anything.
Of course, that worried me.
And then that same day, invasion, he kind of set up his command post in one of the German bunkers.
And I guess it must have been a shell from one of our ships, and the channel came in a little close.
One of the ranges wrote that it was a marker shell because it was real yellow.
Everything it hit was yellow.
But it came in too close and hit the side of that bunker.
And the men on either side of Earl were killed.
And he was left standing, but he got shrapnel in his hip and his arm.
I think I may have a picture of that bunker, but you don't need to see it, I'm sure.
You'll take my word for it, won't you?
Sure.
Oh, yes.
When I first met Omar Bradley...
in 1980 after we got to El Paso.
I wondered if he was in El Paso.
Yes, ma'am.
He was in a wheelchair by then.
Oh, yeah.
Had his stroke.
But he was still very sharp.
Yeah.
And he looked up at me and said, you're from A&M.
Yes, sir.
Did you know Earl Rutter?
Yes, sir.
Worked with him.
His voice then broke a little, and he said, in 48 years of command responsibility, I never gave a more awful order.
than the one I gave to him the morning of D-Day, because if they hadn't succeeded, we would have had a massacre on both beaches.
Well, in his book, A Soldier's Story, he says that.
No soldier in my command has ever been wished a more difficult task than that which befell this 34-year-old.
I know the thing by heart.
And it was.
It was something.
All right, then, so it goes on through the Battle of the Bulge.
When do you see him after the war is over?
I don't remember it.
It's funny, I don't remember the exact date.
